:"1415","1469":"1469","1402":"1402","before September 1436":"before September 1436","about 1415":"about 1415","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1387":"1387","1430":"1430","1383":"1383","about 1430":"about 1430","Beechworth, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Betchworth, Surrey, England":"Betchworth, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Arundel Castle, Sussex, England":"Arundel Castle, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French  <i>muine</i>,  <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’. Some of the following early bearers without the definite article could alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Moon   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Moin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Moyne</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>muine</i>, <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): unexplained."]},{"name":"Moon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Mohan  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Moyon in La Manche. Compare   Mounce  .","Americanized form of German   Mohn   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Moynan","meanings":["Irish: perhaps a diminutive of   Moyne   or a reduced form of   Moynihan  ."]},{"name":"Moine","meanings":["French: from <i>moine</i> ‘monk’, probably applied as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."]},{"name":"Moynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyne   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Moyne was born in 1402, in Betchworth, Surrey, England, her father, Henry le Moyns II, was 26 and her mother, Ann Scudamore, was 19. She married John Burdon before September 1436. She died in 1444, in Betchworth, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1402–1444":"1402–1444","1387–1430":"1387–1430","–Male":"Surnud","1415–1469":"1415–1469","1376–1402":"1376–1402","1383–1430":"1383–1430","1415":"1415","1469":"1469","14